-- Stocks in South Africa Advance to Highest Since June 2008, Led by Billiton
-- B y   G a r t h   T h e u n i s s e n   a n d   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a
-- 2010-11-04T15:57:14Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-04/stocks-in-south-africa-advance-to-highest-since-june-2008-led-by-billiton.html
South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index  rose for the fifth time in six days, adding 509.93,
or 1.7 percent, to 31,327.90 at the 5 p.m. close in
Johannesburg, the highest since June 2008.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.  Anglo American Plc  (AGL SJ), the diversified mining company
that makes up about 10 percent of South Africa’s benchmark stock
index, added 6.86 rand, or 2.1 percent, to 330.01 rand, the
highest since April 26. Copper advanced to a 28-month high as
the Federal Reserve pledged more stimulus money to bolster the
economy in the U.S., the world’s second-largest buyer of the
metal. Lead, nickel, tin and zinc prices climbed.  Anglo Platinum Ltd.  (AMS SJ), the biggest producer of the
metal, increased 18.38 rand, or 2.7 percent, to 704.38 rand,
snapping two days of declines. Platinum surged as much as 3.5
percent to $1,755.63 rand.  Impala Platinum Holdings Ltd.  (IMP SJ), the second-largest
producer of the metal, surged 10.10 rand, or 5.2 percent, to
205.10 rand.  BHP Billiton Plc  (BIL SJ), the world’s biggest mining
company, rallied 15.50 rand, or 6.2 percent, to 267.50 rand, the
highest since July 2008, on investor expectation the company
won’t spend $40 billion buying Potash Corp. of Saskatchewan Inc.
and may turn to a buyback. Canada blocked Billiton’s bid for
Potash. The company now has 20 days to appeal and said today it
will review its options.  Comair Ltd.  (COM SJ), the airline company that operates a
franchise agreement with British Airways Plc in South Africa,
rose 10 cents, or 4.4 percent, to 2.35 rand, extending its gain
in the past two days to 10 percent. The company was raised to
“hold” from “‘sell” by Investec equity analyst  Giuseppe Jerman , who set a 12-month price estimate of 230 rand a share.  Gold Fields Ltd.  (GFI SJ), Africa’s second-largest gold
producer, rose for the first time in four days, gaining 3.05
rand, or 2.8 percent, to 111 rand, the highest since Sept. 14.
The gold miner said first-quarter production of the precious
metal climbed to the highest in two-and-a-half years.  Harmony Gold Mining Ltd.  (HAR SJ), Africa’s third-biggest
producer of the metal, increased for a second day, adding 1.25
rand, or 1.6 percent, to 80.25 rand. Gold rallied as much as 3.5
percent to $1,384.10 an ounce.  Invicta Holdings Ltd.  (IVT SJ), an engineering company,
surged the most in two weeks, climbing 1.99 rand, or 5.2
percent, to 40 rand. The company said earnings per share are
expected to be as much as 18 percent higher in the six months to
Sept. 30 when compared to the corresponding period the previous
year, according to a stock-exchange statement.  Sasol Ltd.  (SOL SJ), the world’s biggest maker of motor
fuel from coal, rose for a second day, advancing 3.56 rand, or
1.1 percent, to 325.48 rand. Oil gained as much as 2.4 percent
to $86.68 a barrel.  Sun International Ltd.  (SUI SJ), South Africa’s largest
gaming and leisure company, increased for the third day, gaining
2.84 rand, or 2.9 percent, to 101.50 rand. The company said
revenue for the three months through September rose 11 percent
to 2.2 billion rand ($324 million) from a year earlier,
according to a statement.  Truworths International Ltd.  (TRU SJ), South Africa’s
largest publicly traded clothing retailer by market value,
climbed for a sixth day, advancing 1.31 rand, or 1.8 percent, to
74 rand, the highest close since the shares started trading in
May 1998. Sales for the 18 weeks to Oct. 31 increased by 14.7
percent compared with the same period a year earlier, the Cape
Town-based company said.  To contact the reporters on this story:
